g.text: Learning and exploring digital possibilities through prototyping
How can we best apply digital methods to explore, understand, or present our
collections? This poster presents some questions that arose during an
experiment in building digital prototypes to facilitate interdisciplinary
collaboration and co
learning between digital and collections specialists.
Topic modelling statistically analyses
documents to find words that are
important in a topic. It can tell us what
the words are, how important to the
topic they are, and which documents
the topic appears in.
But it cannot tell us what the actual
topic is. We
have to
interpret the
model to make sense of it.
On the right are models of topics found
in Wellcome Collection’s 18
th
century
books. The models are represented as
word clouds. Ideally, each cloud will
represent some meaningful topic in
the books.
Some clouds may describe just one
book, others a theme that cuts across
some part of the collection. Some may
spark ideas
and some may mean
nothing at all.

g.text: What could these topic models be about?

text.font-family: Supria Sans Cond Medium,Supria Sans Cond Medium_MSFontService,sans-serif

g.text: Questions
Wellcome Collection collects material about health and
human experience. What do the topics suggest about
what can be found in the collection?
Can we trust our interpretations of the topics? Can other
data help us to interpret the topics?
Which topics are useful? Which are meaningless?
How can we use topics to search or explore the
collection? To understand it from a new perspective, or
to inspire questions about it?
This work is part of a TNA/RLUK Professional
Fellowship hosted at Wellcome Collection.
Professional Fellowships pair an employee of
The National Archives with a host organisation
from Research Libraries UK (or vice versa) to
explore a professional practice question.
